            <section>
                <h3>What is Gyoza?</h3>
                <div>
                    <p>Gyoza is a type of Japanese dumpling that is typically filled with ground meat (often pork), vegetables, and seasonings. The filling is then wrapped in a thin dough wrapper and pan-fried or steamed until cooked through. Gyoza is often served as an appetizer or side dish, and it's a popular menu item at Japanese restaurants around the world.
                    <br><br>
                    Gyoza originated in China, where they are known as jiaozi, but they have been adapted and developed into a unique Japanese cuisine. The Japanese version of gyoza is typically smaller and more delicate than their Chinese counterparts, and they're often served with a dipping sauce made from soy sauce, rice vinegar, and chili oil.
                    <br><br>
                    There are many different variations of gyoza, with different fillings and cooking methods. Some common variations include shumai (open-faced dumplings), age-gyoza (deep-fried dumplings), and yaki-gyoza (pan-fried dumplings). Gyoza can also be filled with a variety of different ingredients, such as shrimp, chicken, mushrooms, and cabbage, among others.
                    <br><br>
                    Making gyoza at home can be a fun and rewarding experience, and there are many different recipes and variations available to try.</p>
                </div>
