            <section>
                <h3>Ingredients</h3>
                <ul class="info-list ul-list">
                    <li>1/2 pound ground pork</li>
                    <li>2 cloves garlic, minced</li>
                    <li>1/2 cup green onions, finely chopped</li>
                    <li>1 cup cabbage, finely chopped</li>
                    <li>1 tablespoon soy sauce</li>
                    <li>1 tablespoon sesame oil</li>
                    <li>1 tablespoon cornstarch</li>
                    <li>1/4 teaspoon salt</li>
                    <li>1/4 teaspoon black pepper</li>
                    <li>30 gyoza wrappers</li>
                    <li>1/4 cup water</li>
                    <li>Vegetable oil for cooking</li>
                </ul>

                <p class="list-title">For the dipping sauce:</p>
                <ul class="info-list ul-list">
                    <li>1/4 cup soy sauce</li>
                    <li>2 tablespoons rice vinegar</li>
                    <li>1 tablespoon sesame oil</li>
                    <li>1 tablespoon green onions, finely chopped</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h3>Instructions</h3>
                <ol class="info-list ol-list">
                    <li>In a large mixing bowl, combine the ground pork, garlic, ginger, green onions, cabbage, soy sauce, sesame oil, cornstarch, salt, and black pepper. Mix well until all ingredients are combined evenly.</li>
                    <li>Take one gyoza wrapper and place a tablespoon of the pork filling in the center. Wet the edges of the wrapper with water, then fold in half and press the edges together to seal. Repeat with remaining wrappers and filling.</li>
                    <li>Heat a non-stick skillet over medium heat, and add enough vegetable oil to coat the bottom of the pan.</li>
                    <li>Once the pan is hot, add the gyoza to the pan, flat side down. Cook for 2-3 minutes or until the bottom is golden brown.</li>
                    <li>Pour the water into the pan and cover immediately with a lid. Let the gyoza steam for 5-6 minutes or until cooked through.</li>
                    <li>While the gyoza are cooking, make the dipping sauce by combining the soy sauce, rice vinegar, sesame oil, and chopped green onions in a small bowl.</li>
                    <li>Serve the gyoza hot with the dipping sauce on the side.</li>
                </ol>
                <p><strong>Note:</strong> This recipe makes around 30 gyoza, but you can easily double or halve the recipe depending on how many you need. You can also experiment with different fillings and dipping sauces to create your own unique gyoza recipe!</p>

